# Defining the function for creating boxplot and histogram 
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize)  # creating the 2 subplots
    
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="mediumturquoise")  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    
    if bins:
      sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, color="mediumpurple")
    else: 
      sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, color="mediumpurple")  # For histogram
    
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--")  # Add mean to the histogram
    
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-")  # Add median to the histogram

Part 4: Outlier Detection and Treatment¶

The columns of Product, Gender, Marital Status, Usage, Education, and Fitness take on a predictable range of values as seen earlier. Age and Income boxplots showed outliers, but the range takes on acceptables values.

In [57]:
#let's look at the Miles column more closely
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.boxplot(data=df,x='Miles');

The max number of miles a customer expects to run is 360. This point could be an outlier since it is far from the next highest of 300. To tell if it is a true outlier, the timeframe (week, month, year, etc) would need to be confirmed with the business.

Part 5: Conclusions and Recommendations¶

Conclusions:

A dataset of 180 observations containing customer characteristcs was analyzed. The data covered 3 different treadmill products. The main purpose was to see how customer characteristics varied across the 3 different treadmill products and what insights can help the business best target new customers.

The following conclusions were made:

  1. Most customers are male, have 16 years of eduction, are partnered, use the treadmill 4 times or less per week, and are at an average fitness level. Customers have a median age of 26 and median income of $51k.
  2. As expected, the number of miles a customer expects to run is highly corrleated with the fitness level of the customer and number of times a customer uses the treadmill.
  3. The more education a customer has, the more income the customer makes.
  4. The older the customer is, the more income the customer makes.
  5. Age distributions across the 3 products are similar.
  6. The TM195 treadmill is the most popular.
  7. The TM195 and TM498 customers had very similar characteristics.
  8. Customers of TM798 have a positive correlation between age or income vs. activity level (miles, usage, fitness) vs. a little to no correlation for the customers of TM195 and TM498.
  9. Most customers of TM195 and TM498 have 16 years of education, use the treadmill 3 times/week, and have a fitness level of 3.
  10. Most TM798 customers have 18 years of education, use the treadmill 4 times/week, and have a fitness level of 5.
  11. TM798 male customers are mostly older than female customers.

Recommendations to Business:

  1. The TM195/TM498 and TM798 products help capture two distinct types of customer groups.
  2. The business should market the TM798 product to more educated, wealthy, and fit individuals: customers with high education levels, incomes, number of miles expected to run each week, usage, and fitness levels.
  3. Since the TM195 and TM498 customer characteristics are very similar, it may help to further analyze the cannabilization between the two products and how we can differentiate them from a marketing standpoint.
  4. The business should market the TM195 product to lower-income female customers when deciding whether to market the TM195 or TM498 product, as those customers make up the top customer characteristics of the TM195 product.
  5. The business should target partnered customers over single customers as partnered customers make up the bigger share across all 3 products.

Further Analysis:

  1. Confirm the timeframe for the miles variable to help detect any outliers and re-visualize the relationships after outlier treatment. It may also be beneficial to look at the average number of miles a customer usually runs instead of the expected number.
  2. Get the prices of the treadmill products and see how price may be influencing some of the relationships found among customers of different products.
  3. Understand the functional differences between the TM195 and TM498 products. If they are very similar, it may help explain the customer similarities between the two products.
